	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>thefox</b> [ Sun Jun 12, 2011 12:45 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: General questions about PowerPak</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I use it for testing my own software all the time, much more than playing pirated games. I was just pointing out that it isn't the perfect development tool, because of all the CF card swapping, the fact that you don't get the untouched boot state and the few issues with mapper emulation (mostly related to IRQs).</div>
<br />To get rid of card swapping you can build a USB&lt;-&gt;controller port cable and use a piece of software I wrote (see <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=7520" class="postlink">this thread</a>).
<br />
<br />Also I don't think the IRQ/mapper problems are too bad anymore. But it's true there are differences between the real mappers and the PowerPak versions, sometimes because the behavior is different between different revisions of the original mapper (like MMC1), and sometimes to get better compatibility with existing games. For example the MMC3 WRAM protection is permanently disabled for compatibility with StarTropics.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>infiniteneslives</b> [ Sun Jun 12, 2011 11:45 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">shawnleblanc wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Some members of this forum appear to be designing a couple of new carts,</div><br /><br />Like the NESDEV1? That project seems like instead of creating hardware to support all mappers, like the PowerPak, it's more like a superset of the most advanced cartridge/mapper so that people can use for their game development. Is that right?</div>
<br />
<br />Yeah I'm the guy working on building the NESDEV1 over the next year.
<br />
<br />There are still a lot of details to be ironed out over the summer, but the whole goal is for game development on actual hardware.
<br />
<br />We'd like to provide a "superset" or more common mappers for developers, and also allow someone to make their own mapper by doing something like improving the MMC3 if they chose. 
<br />
<br />It would have a USB and possibly an SD card interface as a source for loading programming the "ROMS"
<br />
<br />Hopefully it will allow game developers to also easily transfer the hardware design to what they would need for production of the game without using donor carts.  The production cart would end up being a bare bones version of the NESDEV1.
<br />
<br />If you have any input on what you'd like to see, I'd love to hear it here:      <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=7656&amp;start=195" class="postlink">http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=7656&amp;start=195</a>

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


